{"key":"post-10740541","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10740541</id>\n<content>The only problem with foil being left on is if it's crimped down tight.&amp;nbsp; It doesn't stop gas exchange, but it can tend to allow the dry verm barrier or other filter to get damp, and a damp filter will lead to contamination.&amp;nbsp; I really noticed this a lot with synthetic filter disks, especially if they were on the inside, such as with plastic lids.&amp;nbsp; I was getting about a ten percent bacterial contamination rate, which is completely unacceptable.&amp;nbsp; By removing the foil and always using metal lids with the filter on top where it stays dry, the problem disappeared.&amp;nbsp; As hyphae said, I'm sure if it's just sitting there loosely, it won't hurt anything.&amp;nbsp; I reuse the foil over and over again, so always write on the glass surface of the jars where it comes off easily between uses.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>10740416</prev>\n<first>9946883</first>\n<last>10740541</last>\n<when>1248584669</when>\n<utime>07/26/09 08:04 AM</utime>\n</post>"}